<OL><br>
<LI> Name server works correctly <b> (10 points) </b>
<P> On receiving a client request, the name server should supply either
the list of servers currently active and their addresses OR the address of
a specific server as requested by the client. Implementation of either one
of the schemes is acceptable.</P>
<br>
<LI> Server registers with the name server  <b> (10 points) </b>
<br>
<P> This is done before the server exits normally. </P><br>
<LI> Server de-registers with the name server  <b> (5 points) </b>
<P> This is done when the server exits normally. </P><br>
<LI> Client robustness  <b> (10 points) </b>
<P> Client programs should not crash if they are trying to connect to a server
that has crashed. Also, they should not wait indefinitely for a request to be
serviced. i.e., there should be a time-out for the requests that are sent out
by the clients. </P><br>
<LI> Servers are concurrent  <b> (10 points) </b>
<P> A server should be able to handle 2 client requests simultaneously. </P><br>
<LI> Results  <b> (20 points) </b>
<P> The ease with which the programs can be executed - use of scripts, well 
defined user interfaces, etc. </P>
<br><br>
<LI> Outputs of progress  <b> (10 points) </b>
<P> IP address, port number, timestamp, server/client name, result. Diagnostic 
messages should be printed whenever a message is received.</P>
